'''1,2,4-Butanetriol trinitrate''' ('''BTTN'''), also called '''butanetriol trinitrate''', is an important military [[propellant]]. It is a colorless to brown explosive liquid.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.amazon.com/1-2-4-Butanetriol-Analysis-Synthesis/dp/B00BVD8Q06|title=1,2,4-Butanetriol: Analysis and Synthesis|last=Pisacane|first=Frank J.|date=1982|publisher=PN}}</ref>

BTTN is used as a [[propellant]] in virtually all single-stage [[missile]]s used by the United States, including the [[AGM-114 Hellfire|Hellfire]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/3450853.stm|title=Bacteria help make missile fuel|date=2004-02-02|access-date=2018-11-02|language=en-GB}}</ref> It is less volatile, less sensitive to shock, and more thermally stable than [[nitroglycerine]],<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ro/books?id=_fmGDgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Chemistry and Technology of Solid Rocket Propellants (A Treatise on Solid Propellants)|last=Varghese|first=T. L.|last2=Krishnamurthy|first2=V. N.|date=2017-01-03|publisher=Allied Publishers|year=|isbn=9789385926334|location=|pages=187|language=en}}</ref> for which it is a promising replacement.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=D.|first=Bhowmik,|last2=S.|first2=Sadavarte, V.|last3=M.|first3=Pande, S.|last4=S.|first4=Saraswat, B.|date=2015|title=An Energetic Binder for the Formulation of Advanced Solid Rocket Propellants|url=http://yadda.icm.edu.pl/baztech/element/bwmeta1.element.baztech-98bc795f-3fcd-4a08-9855-d57a0cdf95c3|journal=Central European Journal of Energetic Materials|volume=Vol. 12, no. 1|pages=147|via=}}</ref>

BTTN as a propellant is often used in a mixture with nitroglycerin.<ref name=":0" /> The mixture can be made by co-nitration of butanetriol and [[glycerol]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=E|first=Farncomb,Robert|last2=A|first2=Carr,Walter|date=1987-07-06|title=Co-Nitration of 1,2,4-Butanetriol and Glycerin.|url=http://www.dtic.mil/docs/citations/ADD013053|language=en}}</ref> BTTN is also used as a [[plasticizer]] in some [[nitrocellulose]]-based propellants.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ro/books?id=uKihDQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Rocket Propulsion Elements|last=Sutton|first=George P.|last2=Biblarz|first2=Oscar|date=2016-11-30|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=9781118753910|language=en}}</ref>

BTTN is manufactured by nitration of [[1,2,4-butanetriol]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gouranlou|first=Farideh|last2=Kohsary|first2=Iraj|date=2010-06-01|title=Synthesis and Characterization of 1,2,4-Butanetrioltrinitrate|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/287002330_Synthesis_and_Characterization_of_124-Butanetrioltrinitrate|journal=Asian Journal of Chemistry|volume=22|pages=4221–4228}}</ref> [[Biotechnological]] manufacture of butanetriol is under intensive research.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cao|first=Yujin|last2=Niu|first2=Wei|last3=Guo|first3=Jiantao|last4=Xian|first4=Mo|last5=Liu|first5=Huizhou|date=2015-12-16|title=Biotechnological production of 1,2,4-butanetriol: An efficient process to synthesize energetic material precursor from renewable biomass|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/srep18149|journal=Scientific Reports|language=En|volume=5|issue=1|doi=10.1038/srep18149|issn=2045-2322}}</ref>

