{{Refimprove|date=March 2012}} The '''Burren Action Group''' was a group of people from [[County Clare]] in [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] who opposed plans by the [[Office of Public Works]] during the 1990s to develop a large scale interpretative centre at [[Mullaghmore, County Clare|Mullaghmore]] in the local [[The Burren|Burren area]].<ref name="Leonard154">{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=tMIJiKtF7ggC&lpg |title= The Environmental Movement in Ireland (Google Books), p. 154|publisher=Springer| date= 2007 |first=Liam |last=Leonard |accessdate=2012-11-13}}</ref>
==Goal== The Group was a collective of concerned locals who fought to maintain the natural integrity of the landscape and to protect the environment from elements of the [[Government of Ireland]] which did not understand what was at stake. They also felt that the Burren and the area of Mullaghmore is a "sacred site" <ref name="Leonard154"/> and holy ground that needed to be defended in a country whose sites of profound historical importance are rapidly disappearing.{{citation needed|date=March 2012}}
==History== In 1992/1993 seven members of the group lodged a complaint against the project with the [[Irish High Court]], which resulted in work being stopped.<ref name="EURlex">{{cite web|url= http://eur-lex.europa.eu/Notice.do?mode=dbl&lang=en&ihmlang=en&lng1=en,de&lng2=da,de,el,en,es,fr,it,nl,pt,&val=203965:cs&page= |title=European Court of Justice case|publisher=European Commission| date= |first=|last=|accessdate=2012-11-12}}</ref> These seven included local farmers like James Howard and Patrick McCormack, priest Fr. John O’Donohue, Prof. [[Emer Colleran]] as well as media figures like the producer P.J. Curtis or [[Lelia Doolan]].<ref name="Leonard147">{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=tMIJiKtF7ggC&lpg |title= The Environmental Movement in Ireland (Google Books), p. 150|publisher=Springer| date= 2007 |first=Liam |last=Leonard |accessdate=2012-11-13}}</ref> The Burren Action Group was also supported by leftist politicians like [[Brigid Makowski]].
Following about ten years of opposition, the group was finally successful in March 2000. [[An Bord Pleanála]] confirmed the ruling by the [[Clare County Council]] to refuse planning permission for a scaled-down version of the original plans.<ref name="RTE2">{{cite web|url= http://www.rte.ie/news/2000/0306/burren.html |title=Planning permission refused for Burren centre|publisher=RTÉ| date= 6 March 2000 |first= |last= |accessdate=2012-11-13}}</ref>
In 2012, James Howard and Patrick McCormack, the latter owner of the house that featured as the parochial house in the [[Father Ted]] TV show, once again opposed a new application to construct a car park at the site of the planned visitors' centre.<ref name="Independent">{{cite web|url= http://www.independent.ie/national-news/owner-of-father-ted-house-battles-burren-carpark-plan-3350765.html |title=Owner of 'Father Ted' house battles Burren carpark plan|publisher=Irish Independent| date= 14 January 2013 |first= Gordon|last=Deegan |accessdate=2013-01-29}}</ref>
==Fundraising== The Burren Action Group compiled a [[Album|music album]] in the early 1990s, entitled ''Music in the Stone'' to raise money to save Mullaghmore because ''"...the wheels of greed are rolling towards it"''.<ref>[http://homepages.iol.ie/~burrenag/tape.htm Music in the Stone] April 1993.</ref>
