'''Colbún '''is a [[Public utility|utility]] company in [[Chile]] engaged in the [[electric power transmission]] segment. The company was created in 1982 and [[privatized]] in 1997. Originally it had only two [[hydroelectric plant]]s, [[Machicura]] and [[Colbún Hydroelectric Plant|Colbún]] from where it gets its name. Today Colbún S.A. generates a total of 2514 [[Megawatt|MW]], of which 1274 comes from [[hydropower]] and 1236 from fossil fuels plants.<ref name=colb>{{es icon}}[http://www.colbun.cl/quienes_somos/index.html Quienes somos] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090323132338/http://www.colbun.cl/quienes_somos/index.html |date=2009-03-23 }} by Colbún S.A.</ref> Colbún S.A. supplies the [[Sistema Interconectado Central]] [[power grid]] that spans [[Zona Central, Chile|Zona Central]] and [[Zona Sur]] but is currently developing a controversial [[joint venture]] project with [[ENDESA (Chile)|ENDESA]], called [[HidroAysén]], to create five hydroelectrical power plants in [[Aisén Region]].

In 1997, CORFO sold its 37.5% share, and in March 1997 was fully privatized. The main shareholders are Minera Valparaiso SA (Group Matte) (34.97%) and Electropacífico Investment Ltd. (28.60%).

