{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}} {{Use Australian English|date=January 2015}} {{Infobox power station | name = Crows Nest Wind Farm | name_official = | image = | image_size = | image_caption = | image_alt = | location_map = Queensland | location_map_size = | location_map_caption = | coordinates = {{coord|27|13|51|S|151|57|34|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | country = Australia | location = [[Crows Nest, Queensland]] | status = Approved | construction_began = | commissioned = | decommissioned = | cost = $270,000,000 | owner = [[AGL Energy]] | operator = | ps_units_manu_model = | wind_hub_height = | wind_rotor_diameter = | wind_rated_speed = | wind_farm_type = | wind_site_elevation = | wind_site_usage = | wind_site_area = | wind_offshore_depth = | wind_offshore_distance = | ps_electrical_capacity = 200 [[Megawatt|MW]] | ps_electrical_cap_fac = | website = | extra = }} The proposed '''Crows Nest Wind Farm''', will be located in south-eastern [[Queensland]], 40 kilometres north of [[Toowoomba]]. It initially was to have an installed generating capacity of 124 MW that would produce intermittent electricity that could power some 47,000 homes during periods of high wind. It is expected that the [[wind farm]] will create 460 manufacturing and construction jobs and a further 15 full-time maintenance jobs in [[Crows Nest, Queensland|Crows Nest]]. The Crows Nest location on the western edge of the [[Darling Downs]], offers some of the best average wind speeds available in Queensland, and the project will provide additional security of electricity supply in this fast-growing area.<ref>[http://www.allco.com.au/dm_documents/061213%20Crows%20Nest%20Wind%20Farm%20receives%20Development%20Consent_noE3-.pdf Crows Nest Wind Farm receives Development Consent]</ref>
The project was acquired by [[AGL Energy]] in 2009 after purchasing it and another wind farm at Barn Hill in South Australia from [[Transfield Services]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.brisbanetimes.com.au/breaking-news-business/agl-buys-transfield-wind-farm-projects-20090618-citj.html |title=AGL buys Transfield wind farm projects |accessdate=21 May 2010 |date=18 June 2009 |work=[[Brisbane Times]] |publisher=[[Fairfax Digital]] }}</ref> In June 2009, AGL was allowed to increase the number of turbines by 20 units and therefore the output from 124&nbsp;MW to 200&nbsp;MW. The cost of the project is now expecting to be A$270&nbsp;million.<ref name="cnwfga">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thechronicle.com.au/story/2011/02/02/crows-nest-residents-opposed-to-a-giant-wind-farm/ |title=Crows Nest wind farm to go ahead |author=Stuart Cumming |accessdate=28 June 2011 |date=2 February 2011 |newspaper=The Chronicle |publisher=Toowoomba Newspapers Pty Ltd }}</ref>
==Objections== Residents of [[Shire of Crows Nest|Crows Nest Shire]] formed a "No Wind Farm" group which objected to the proposal. The activists contended that [[Wind turbine|turbine]] blades would cause light flicker as they passed the sun, turbines would cause noise, devalue land, be a detriment to fauna and visual appeal of the area and were contrary to the council's town plan. They also argued the green credentials of wind farms were a myth because large amounts of coal-fired energy was needed to power up generators to full capacity after a drop in wind speed. After drawn-out legal proceedings and mediation between the parties, the objections were progressively dropped.<ref>(14 December 2006). [http://www.thechronicle.com.au/?storyid=3713855&thesection=localnews&thesubsection=&thesecondsubsection= Opponents vow to fight wind farm]. ''The Chronicle''. Toowoomba Newspapers Pty Ltd.</ref>
