'''Pentadecanoic acid''' is a saturated [[fatty acid]]. Its molecular formula is CH<sub>3</sub>(CH<sub>2</sub>)<sub>13</sub>COOH. It is rare in nature, being found at the level of 1.2% in the milk fat from cows.<ref>Rolf Jost "Milk and Dairy Products" Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Wiley-VCH, Weinheim, 2002. {{DOI|10.1002/14356007.a16_589.pub3}}</ref> The [[butterfat]] in cows [[milk]] is its major dietary source<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Smedman | first1 = AE | last2 = Gustafsson | first2 = IB | last3 = Berglund | first3 = LG | last4 = Vessby | first4 = BO | title = Pentadecanoic acid in serum as a marker for intake of milk fat: relations between intake of milk fat and metabolic risk factors | journal = The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition | volume = 69 | issue = 1 | pages = 22–9 | year = 1999 | pmid = 9925119}}</ref> and it is used as a marker for butterfat consumption.<ref>[http://www.lipomics.com/fatty_acids/pentadecanoic-acid Pentadecanoic acid], Lipomics.com</ref> Pentadecanoic acid also occurs in hydrogenated mutton fat.<ref>{{cite journal | journal = Biochem. J. | year = 1954 | volume = 58 | pages = 516–517 | pmid = 13229996 | last1 = Hansen | first1 = RP | last2 = Shorland | first2 = FB | last3 = Cooke | first3 = NJ | title = The occurrence of ''n''-pentadecanoic acid in hydrogenated mutton fat | issue = 4 | pmc = 1269934}}</ref> It also comprises 3.61% of the fats from the fruit of the [[durian]] species ''[[Durio graveolens]]''.<ref name="Nasaruddin">{{cite journal|last1=Nasaruddin|first1=Mohd hanif|last2=Noor|first2=Noor Qhairul Izzreen Mohd|last3=Mamat|first3=Hasmadi|title=Komposisi Proksimat dan Komponen Asid Lemak Durian Kuning (Durio graveolens) Sabah|journal=Sains Malaysiana|date=2013|volume=42|issue=9|pages=1283–1288|url=http://www.ukm.my/jsm/pdf_files/SM-PDF-42-9-2013/11%20Mohd%20Hanif.pdf|accessdate=28 November 2017|trans-title=Proximate and Fatty Acid Composition of Sabah Yellow Durian (Durio graveolens)|language=Malay|format=PDF|issn=0126-6039|oclc=857479186}}</ref>
Pentadecanoic acid may increase mother-to-child transmission of HIV through breastfeeding.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 17823433 | year = 2007 | last1 = Villamor | first1 = E | last2 = Koulinska | first2 = IN | last3 = Furtado | first3 = J | last4 = Baylin | first4 = A | last5 = Aboud | first5 = S | last6 = Manji | first6 = K | last7 = Campos | first7 = H | last8 = Fawzi | first8 = WW | title = Long-chain ''n''-6 polyunsaturated fatty acids in breast milk decrease the risk of HIV transmission through breastfeeding | volume = 86 | issue = 3 | pages = 682–9 | journal = The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition}}</ref>
